is to estimate physical quantities of the lens system. From this, we find\nthat the lens system has a star with mass $M_{\\rm h}=0.55^{+0.36}_{-0.29} \\\nM_{\\odot}$ hosting a giant planet with $M_{\\rm p}=5.53^{+3.62}_{-2.87} \\ M_{\\rm\nJup}$, at a distance of $D_{\\rm L}=5.67^{+1.11}_{-1.52}\\ {\\rm kpc}$. The\nprojected star-planet separation in units of the Einstein radius $(\\theta_{\\rm\nE})$ corresponding to the total mass of the lens system is\n$a_{\\perp}=3.92^{+1.10}_{-1.32}\\ \\rm{au}$. This means that the planet is\nlocated beyond the snow line of the host. The relative lens-source proper\nmotion is $\\mu_{\\rm rel}\\sim 7 \\ \\rm{mas \\ yr^{-1}}$, thus the lens and source\nwill be separated from each other within 10 years. Then the flux of the host\nstar can be measured by a 30m class telescope with high-resolution imaging in\nthe future, and thus its mass can be determined.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 21 Dec 2020 02:09:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 22 Dec 2020 05:54:27 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 25 Feb 2021 22:25:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-03-01"}
